  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>This foundational stage is one of the most critical, as it sets the stage for the entire project. Errors or oversights here can cause significant delays and budget overruns. It involves transforming a raw piece of land into a build-ready site while navigating the necessary legal and administrative hurdles.</p>

    <h3>Surveyor Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Property Line and Setback Identification</h4>
    <p>The surveyor researches the legal plat of the property to identify the exact boundaries. They physically locate and mark the property corners with stakes and flagging. They also mark the building setbacks, which are the minimum distances the structure must be from the property lines, as dictated by local zoning ordinances.</p>

    <h4>House Staking</h4>
    <p>Using the approved architectural plans, the surveyor stakes out the precise footprint of the house on the lot. This includes marking the corners of the foundation and any other critical points that the excavation and foundation contractors will use as a guide. The stakes must be accurate to within a fraction of an inch to ensure the house is built in the correct location and orientation.</p>

    <h3>Site Prep Contractor Activities</h3>
    <h4>Clearing and Grubbing</h4>
    <p>All trees, brush, and vegetation within the construction zone are removed. Trees designated to be saved are clearly marked and protected. The root systems of removed trees are grubbed out to prevent future settling and decay.</p>

    <h4>Erosion Control</h4>
    <p>Silt fences or other erosion control measures are installed around the perimeter of the disturbed area to prevent soil from washing off-site during rain, a common requirement before any major grading can begin.</p>

    <h4>Rough Grading</h4>
    <p>Using heavy equipment like bulldozers and graders, the contractor reshapes the lot to create the basic contours for proper drainage, as shown on the site plan. This involves cutting high spots and filling low spots to create a level building pad and to ensure water will flow away from the future foundation.</p>

    <h4>Access Road and Staging Area</h4>
    <p>A temporary construction driveway is created using gravel or crushed rock to provide a stable surface for heavy vehicles and to minimize mud being tracked onto public roads. A staging area is designated for material deliveries and parking.</p>

    <h4>Temporary Utilities</h4>
    <p>A temporary electrical pole and panel are installed by a licensed electrician and inspected by the utility company. A temporary water meter or connection to a well is established for construction use.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Role</h3>
    <h4>Permit Review and Approval</h4>
    <p>The inspector or plans examiner meticulously reviews the submitted building plans and engineering documents for compliance with all local building codes, zoning laws, and ordinances. This includes structural, electrical, plumbing, mechanical, and energy codes. Once approved, the building permit is issued, which must be prominently displayed on the job site.</p>

    <h4>Initial Site/Erosion Control Inspection</h4>
    <p>Before major earthmoving, an inspector may visit the site to verify that the required erosion control measures are correctly installed. They will check that the silt fence is properly trenched and staked to effectively contain sediment.</p>

    <h3>Construction Manager Oversight</h3>
    <h4>Coordination and Scheduling</h4>
    <p>The CM schedules the surveyor and site prep contractor in the correct sequence. They ensure that the surveyor has the final approved plans to work from.</p>

    <h4>Permitting and Documentation</h4>
    <p>The CM is responsible for compiling and submitting the complete permit application package to the city, which may include multiple sets of plans, engineering calculations, soil reports, and other documents. They track the permit through the review process and respond to any questions or requests for additional information from the city.</p>

    <h4>Pre-Construction Verification</h4>
    <p>The CM verifies that all conditions from the land department or developer have been met before work begins (e.g., architectural review committee approval, tree preservation plans).</p>

    <h4>Site Logistics and Safety</h4>
    <p>The CM establishes the site layout, including the location of the temporary utilities, construction entrance, material storage, and waste dumpster. A comprehensive site safety plan is developed and communicated to all trade partners, including requirements for personal protective equipment (PPE) and emergency procedures.</p>
