  <section class="content-section">
    <h2>Overview</h2>
    <p>During the framing stage, the house transforms from a concrete slab into a recognizable structure. This is often considered one of the most exciting phases for a homeowner to watch. The framing creates the "skeleton" of the house, defining all the rooms, walls, and rooflines. Accuracy is critical, as all subsequent trades will rely on the framing being plumb, level, and square.</p>

    <h3>Framing Contractor Responsibilities</h3>
    <h4>Floor System Construction</h4>
    <p>The contractor lays down a sill plate, which is pressure-treated lumber bolted directly to the foundation wall. Floor joists (or pre-engineered floor trusses) are set on top of the sill plate, spaced according to the plans (typically 16 or 24 inches on center). Rim joists are installed around the perimeter. The subfloor, typically 3/4-inch plywood or OSB (Oriented Strand Board), is glued and nailed to the joists, creating the walking surface for the first floor.</p>

    <h4>Wall Assembly</h4>
    <p>Walls are typically assembled on the subfloor and then lifted into place. Each wall section consists of top and bottom plates, vertical studs, and headers over window and door openings. Exterior walls are sheathed with plywood or OSB, which adds significant structural strength and a nailing surface for siding.</p>

    <h4>Roof and Ceiling Assembly</h4>
    <p>Ceiling joists are installed to form the structure of the ceiling. The roof is constructed using either pre-fabricated trusses delivered to the site or by stick-building with individual rafters. The trusses or rafters are lifted into place (often with a crane) and secured, creating the pitch and shape of the roof. The roof is then sheathed with OSB or plywood, creating the roof deck.</p>

    <h4>Window and Door Installation</h4>
    <p>Windows and exterior doors are installed into the prepared openings. Proper flashing and sealing around these units are critical to prevent water intrusion.</p>

    <h3>City Inspector Requirements</h3>
    <h4>Framing Inspection (Shear/Structural Inspection)</h4>
    <p>This is one of the most comprehensive and critical inspections. The inspector will walk the entire structure, often with the plans in hand.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Structural Integrity:</strong> They verify that all lumber and beams are the correct size and grade, that joist and rafter spans are not exceeded, and that all structural connections (e.g., hurricane ties, anchor bolts) are correctly installed.</li>
      <li><strong>Load Path:</strong> The inspector checks to ensure there is a continuous load path, meaning the weight from the roof is properly transferred all the way down to the foundation.</li>
      <li><strong>Nailing and Fastening:</strong> They will check the nailing patterns on the sheathing and other structural components to ensure they meet the required shear strength.</li>
      <li><strong>Openings:</strong> Headers over windows and doors are checked to ensure they are sized correctly for the load they are carrying.</li>
      <li><strong>Code Compliance:</strong> The inspector checks for compliance with numerous other code requirements, such as fire blocking between floors and in specific wall cavities.</li>
    </ul>

